I needed a universal cross key like this one for my job. Found one on the thingiverse, but I found it not strong enough. So I decided to design my own.
Used dimensions found on the internet and designed it with Autodesk Inventor professional 2015. Just load the .stl, scale 10x, rotate 90* on x- or y-axis and start printing.
Don't forget to enable support material. You might be able to print without, but for the best results you need some support. For more tips on this print, see instructions. If you want to edit this thing, feel free to do so. I've added the .ipt file for easy editing. (10x scale has something to do with my inventor settings. When I export the .ipt to .stl, it automaticaly scales it down for some reason. Just scale it up 10x and you are good to go)
Pls post a comment with your pros, cons and tips!
Srry for my English, it's not my primary.

Enable supportmaterial - Some ends of this key are smaller then de key itself and therefore they are not touching the printbed. Use supportmaterial to solve this problem. I used Slic3r and made it detect where supportmaterial is needed  
Minimal 4 Perimiters - For better printresults on banked edges and a stronger key, use minimal 4 perimiters.  
Minimal 30% Infill - To print a strong key, use minimal 30% infill. You can use more, but the ends are much more likely to break at 30% already.

description.text: This gimbal mounted magnet probe is a classic for everybody working   with magnetic fields. I realized the 3D design with Design Spark. The  two example magnet probes were printed with orange and black PLA (1.75 mm) on my German RepRap NEO 3D printer. I used NdB permanent magnets (length = 24 mm, diameter = 4 mm). I used red and blue nail polish to reveal the probe orientation. The gimbal is mounted with 4 headless screws (length = 5 mm, diameter = 2 mm). The screws hold the gimbal rings and allow to fine-tune them for free rotation. You'll need a quite small hex key for such small screws.

comments.text: This thing is simply a tool which allows getting a qualitative idea about magnetic vector fields, e.g. the field lines around a permanent magnet. It is also a nice tool to determine the field orientation of an electromagnetic coil. That's actually why it is a good idea to put some paint on the magnet's tips (see picture). Of course, the magnet will be attraced by ferromagnetic 3d-metals like Fe, Co and Ni. Any other ferromagnetic, ferrimagnetic or paramagnetic material will also be attracted. This thing is not something like a camera gimbal but a gimbal-mounted (universal-mounted, cardanic) permanent magnet with two freely rotating axes. If mechanical friction is low enough, which is the case for both tools I 3D printed, the magnet orients along the magnetic field lines of the earth. Or in other words, this tool acts like a compass with an additional axis of rotation.

title: MK(7/8/other) 40mm Fan to Nema-motor mount relief!

description.text:
If anybody noticed, what rounding can lead to: nema 17 -> holes for screws are on 1.7inch circle = 43.18mm (circle diameter), so if you draw a square on the 4 points of attachments, the distance is ca. 30.53 mm. Fanholes of a 40mm fan, are mostly ca. around 32mm spaced apart.
-> That is in total a difference of 32-30.53=1.47mm, not much, and for sure the clearance helps that all screws fit and go through, but they do not really lineup with the holes. So this design fixes the different distances (and also pushes the air up/gets it from above depending on how you mount your fan, because of screw-clearence). There are 2 versions: One for direct mount for a 40mm fan only. One is specific for the thing-o-matic (and maybe also rep1 and rep2 but not tested) with a cooling pipe down to the nozzle. Used this with MB40201VX-000U-A99 fan, works good. M3 holes need post-processing. Only for educational and non-commercial use.

Grip for mounting on a 40 mm outer diameter pipe build of a Blastech E11 action replica. Or a Sterling SMG, if you'd rather build one of those. Based mainly on reference files from the Blaster Builders Club and somewhat on other various sources and pictures from the web. There are cavities for a tact switch and a 6,6 mm potentiometer inside the grip for the trigger and the fire mode switch respectively. These are intended as inputs for an Arduino. Go bananas with addressable RGBs and a sound module, if you like. Oh, and there's room for a spring, or half a spring from a retractable ball point pen or similar for the trigger action. This is made to go with the Hengstler counter I've published earlier. Made for a cheap extruder printer that doesn't like bridging or overhangs very much. Any 3D-printer should be able to print this, but I've not printed this myself yet, so there could be structural errors that have slipped by netfabb.

Use the reference stl of the assembled grip to see how this goes together. It's not rocket science, and you're a maker, right? The assembled grip is not meant for printing, as it contains too many internal structures that I couldn't be arsed to remove. Besides, the point of this grip is to make a blaster prop with sound and light. A grip printed in one block of plastic would make mounting the sensors pretty hard.

I also agree with CaptainObvious about the lifting horizontal stabilizer. A lifting stab CAN be used but it makes the design more difficult. KISS. I would rethink the fuselage design so that the nose moment is much shorter. Ideally you would want the battery pack to be near the CG so that you can go up or down in size (weight) without having to rebalance the plane. The fuselage design is very good in that it is made up of modules that can be added or removed so plan on having at least one of them behind the wing. A fairing on the last fuselage module that comes to a point will go a long way in reducing drag. What airfoil are you using? The leading edge is very sharp and will cause the airplane to be pitch sensitive. I would recommend using a Clark-Y airfoil. You can get the coordinates and then plot the airfoil in the 2D mode and then extrude it. Do you have an idea of the overall weight and the power needed? Keep up the good work!

description.text:
This is a safety razor blade bank.  You put your old blades into this box for safe disposal.   
This is one solid piece of pla.  The top is curved to allow it to be printed without the use of supports, keeping the interior hollow for the used blades. As such, there is no assembly required, simply print and use.  All walls are 4mm thick and the end result is very sturdy.

I printed on a replicator 2 using PLA with 25% infill at makerware's "high" profile presets (0.1mm layer height).  I picked the higher res since the smaller steps and slower process may help the top correctly form without it caving in.  It has worked well.  A larger layer height may or may not work, I have not tried it personally.  
And again, feel free to use rafts, but DO NOT use supports.

description.text: Made with cookie caster app

A difficult print. It only managed to print 10% of the time for me, and your mileage may vary. I'll certainly adhere more rigidly to good FDM design next time! Let me know if there is interest in this particular character, and I'll make a more printable pose for her. Hatsune Miku is a mascot character for the Vocaloid software. Original model by Kio and is also subject to the terms of his license.

I mostly used this pose as an excuse to experiment with various support pillaring techniques.  
Flat, 1-2 filament wide columns seem to give fairly good payoff for how easy they are to remove from convex surfaces that they support.  Non-convex intersections with the model required tooling or sanding.  Because these pillars are long and narrow, they can easily pull themselves off the platform when the plastic cools, so it's good to boolean little cones to them, especially on the edges of a pillar.

This a work in progress.  I am experimenting with different settings and text to get the best lettering.  This is the first design I have made for a business card.  Overall I think the design itself looks great (aside from letters and numbers).  
Comments and input are appreciated!  If you have experience making small text look good please let me know!  
UPDATE 3/19/15:  I made a silver version with an extrude subtract by .6mm.  The total thickness is 1mm.  You can see that the Redbird logo is subtracted all the way through.  I also increased the text size quite a bit.  
UPDATE 3/25/15:  I was able to get red text on top with a nice transition.  I added a square off the the side so I could change the filament while it was filling the box.  The last picture shows the current version.  The top has the transparent red while the bottom has the opaque red. (the top is version 4 and bottom is version 5)   
UPDATE 4/21/2015: After using different flow rates and retraction rates I found the perfect combination.  The last three photos are the finalized business card design I made. Overall thickness of card is 0.5mm.  (0.2mm for first layer and 0.15 mm for the second 2 layers.)  Overall layer height with text is 0.8mm.  Flow rate for the printer I'm using is set to 670 with a retraction rate of 1.5mm. (other printers will vary)  
UPDATE 4/23/2015: Cover photo is now the final design.  The second photo (all black) is the first design.  
UPDATE 7/5/2015: Newest cover photo is now the NEW final design (I think).  Now the second photo is the old final design.  I used a 0.2 mm nozzle to get smaller text.  The new Slic3r also gave  it a new fill pattern.  
UPDATE 8/1/2015: I have redesigned the card to have a different look with the logo.  You can see it in the second photo shown.  (still a little rough getting that fill just right)  
UPDATE 9/16/2015: I have added a QR code which links to my 3D Hubs webpage.  First picture is the new card.

The card is 1 mm thick (two layers at .3mm and first layer at .4mm).  I may do an extrude-subtract procedure to see how different the text will look.  The card is somewhat flexible but will definitely snap if you try to break it.  I may try using semi-flex PLA if we get some in.  Also this part was made using NX 9.0.  I used slic3r to slice the file and the fill pattern is the octagramspiral.

title: Scan-O-Tron Turntable v.2.0 for Full Body 3D Scanning

description.text:
A 3D scanning turntable capable of supporting the weight of one or more human beings (I think its good to over 800 lbs as long as the weight is evenly distributed). To be used in conjunction with The Scan-O-Tron 3000 http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:127968 as a low cost, quick and high quality scanning system for creating 3D printable full body scans. This 2.0 design replaces my previous design Heavy Duty Lazy Susan for Full Body Scanning http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:28454 by improving from a belt drive mechanism to a chain and sprocket drive powered by a worm gear motor. This ensures the tabletop is locked for better loading and unloading of subjects. This is the hardware design that I use in the Scan-A-Rama 3D Portrait Studio http://scanarama3d.com. I recommend ReconstructMe as scanning software for doing full body scans, but Skanect is another great option. http://youtu.be/2c_Pa0ppzV0
  • Scan cleanup routine with Netfabb basic:
    https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9ZVc-CpVLrs

I uploaded a series of images detailing the process. Parts utilize include
  • 3/4" plywood
  • Car Hub for lode bearing bearing (I used Wheel Hub Assembly Fit for BMW 525I 528I 530I 540I Z8 Front)
  • Number 25 electric scooter chain (I bought this from http://www.electricscooterparts.com/chain25.html)
  • 16 Tooth 8mm Bore Sprocket For #25 Chain (SPR-2516) from http://www.electricscooterparts.com/sprockets25chain-motor.html
  • 90 Tooth Rear Sprocket For #25 Chain (SPR-2590) from http://www.electricscooterparts.com/sprockets25chain-wheel.html
  • 12 volt AC/DC adapter
  • I use a foot pedal switch such as http://www.harborfreight.com/power-maintained-foot-switch-96618.html to turn on and off the turntable while scanning.
    • You will need a chain breaker tool, a socket wrench, and a bunch of 3/8" lag bolts with washers and nuts. A router to cut your circles is also great. Cut list from 3/4" plywood
  • 28" square
  • 2- 28" circles
  • 2- 6 1/2" circles
  • 15" square, with circle for the hub cut in the center
  • 15" circle
    • Ream out the 2 6 1/2" circles so the large sprocket can be sandwiched fluch between them. Bolt together the car hub, 6 1/2" circle, large sprocket, other 6 1/2" circle, and 15" circle with 3/8" bolts. Glue and screw together the 28" square and 15" square, the bolt the hub to it with 3/8" bolts. Screw 4 2x4 feet on the corners of the large square. Use some 2x4 to build a small frame around the 15" square and drill 4 holes in it. Mount the motor to a piece of 2x4 and put the small sprocket on the motor. Use the chain breaker to cut a piece of chain to go around both sprockets and then rejoin the chain. Drill matching 4 holes in the 2x4 with the motor and put long bolts through so that each 2x4 has a pair of bolts around it and you can adjust the tension on the chain to pull it tight. Glue and screw together the 2 28" circles. Drill holes and bolt the 28" circles to the 15" circle on the hub.

description.text:
This is my take on Hobby kings SK450 frames. We got 2 plug and fly Turnigy SK450 quads while they had there big sale. For the price is is a good quad. We ordered them as the sale price was less then the electronics by them selves. I was at home sick and could not do much out side of tinker with my new toy. I did force some testing in to get things set.
As I sat there and fiddled with my quad I had some ideas. I sat down with calipers and hex wrenches in hand I set out to map the important hole placements. In the end I have a few options to pick from. The bottom frame in standard and extended style. Plus top frame / flight controller mount in 2 styles, vertical and slanted damping. The vertical style should work with both gimbal dampers or earplugs. The slanted (45d) is for earplug dampers. I have also included a dxf file (in inches) for anyone who wants to cnc or laser cut a set.
I am early in the design but it helps to get input. This is all prototype form untested so think of that before jumping in. I will be adding more goodies in for addons as I keep going. One planed setup is retractable landing gear for ap.
Thanks go to hobbyking and turnigy for this nice quad to spark my creativity.

that and truly will not protect (or filter) the wavelengths as stated in
the ads. THis has been documented by Euro Optical Specialities, Independent
and Government sponsored laboratory tests and Customer Advocacy groups. I
plan to buy a large sheet of approved, certified wavelength-specific protective filtering material ($$$) (Probably from Photonics) and cut a
strip off that I can heat slightly and form around my laser head. This will
also be capped at the top with the same material which will be 'raised' just above the cutting/engraving/burning or fusing job during fast positioning movements, and lowered by
a solenoid when LASER is again active. All LASER wavelengths from RED thru UV will totally destroy
your eyes. Even bounce of reflected LASER light while engraving, cutting or fusing from
floors, walls, ceilings and ...'chromed X-Y an Z tubing' will cause permanent retinal damage.
